SPECIES COMMENTS: 1st documented Santa Cruz County record.------in view for about 15 minutes total. 4-15 m distance. Nice lighting.--------Overall Impression:  Relatively drab Dendroica with two white wingbars, yellowish-green above, pale buff below with traces of pinkish or chestnut color on sides.----Size:  Very similar to adjacent Townsend's Warblers (D. townsendi).  ----Head: Crown was yellowish-green with no streaking evident. Narrow yellow supercilium (not prominent).  Dusky gray eyeline (indistinct and not prominent). Malar region becoming dull whitish-buff. Nape and auriculars were unmarked yellowish-green, a bit brighter than the crown.----Eyes: Dark with narrow whitish or off-white eye arcs (evident only with good, close views)----Bill:  Dark upper mandible, dusky but paler lower mandible.  Size and shape were similar to Townsend's Warbler's bill, but was perhaps a bit larger-billed than Townsend's----Upperparts: Yellowish-green with indistinct dusky streaking on back.  Streaking was not prominent and was most evident only on good, close views.  Rump and uppertail coverts not well seen, but glimpses showed a light grayish-green color.  I didn't see those feathers well enough to tell whether there were any markings on them.----Wings: Blackish with two prominent white wingbars and white highlights on the edges of the tertials.----Underparts: Pale buff with buff tones most prominent on breast and sides. No streaking noticed even with good, close views.  Underparts were palest on chin and belly coverts. The undertail coverts were quite pale buff.   The sides had a few small traces of pinkish or chestnut color and in good light I had the impression of the sides and flanks being lightly washed with pinkish.    ----Tail: Blackish above, paler below.  Prominent white "tail spots". ----Legs, Feet and Toes:  Blackish or gray; no pinkish, flesh or any pale coloring evident. ----Calls: A high, fairly loud "seep", quite unlike the calls of the adjacent Townsend's Warblers ----Behavior:  This bird was feeding on newly-emerging termites with four Townsend's Warblers.  ----Habitat: foraging along a permanent stream, bordered by deciduous alder - cottonwood riparian forest----Comparison to Other Species: This warbler's general appearance immediately suggested to me it was one of the group of Dendroica including Bay-breasted, Blackpoll (D. striata) and Pine (D. pinus) warblers. Once I had good looks at it, I thought the traces of pinkish or chestnut on the sides were diagnostic.  Chestnut-sided warbler (D. pensylvanica) might also show traces of such color on the sides, but it looks quite different otherwise during fall, with lime green upperparts, complete white eyering, pale yellowish wingbars and pale gray underparts.  None of the Chestnut-sided Warblers I've seen in California in the fall had were chestnut-sided.----Blackpoll and Pine warblers were both eliminated by the presence of the bay or chestnut color on the sides.  Blackpoll was further eliminated by the following points.  It has at least faint streaking on the sides and breast.  Its crown is usually duller and less yellowish-green.  Its face pattern (supercilium and eyeline) is more pronounced.  Its back is usually more prominently streaked. Its breast is usually yellowish and its undertail coverts should be white, contrasting with the rest of the underparts.  The all dark legs, feet and toes also supported Bay-breasted Warbler, but didn't eliminate Blackpoll Warbler.  Pine Warbler should lack streaking on the back.  It is less yellowish-green above. It has a distinctive paler area on the side of the neck, lacking on the bird in question. It has white or whitish undertail coverts which contrast with the rest of the underparts.--
